        descLong: "When a C extension segfaults or a thread deadlocks, Python's normal exception machinery is bypassed — you get a SIGSEGV with no traceback, or a hung process with no clue what each thread is doing. `faulthandler` (stdlib since 3.3) hooks the fatal signals at C level and dumps a Python traceback for every thread before the process dies. It can also dump traceback after a timeout (catch hangs) or on a chosen signal (operator-triggered diagnostics). The three examples solve the SAME concrete task — your numpy/torch/protobuf code segfaults intermittently in production; you need a Python traceback at the crash — at three depths: enable() at startup → add hang-detection via `dump_traceback_later` → operator-triggered SIGUSR1 dump and integration with the entrypoint.",
